William Freeman

Executive Summary

This report looks at whether the household income of a student applying to the Georgia Institute of Technology affects their chances of addmission. As technology continues to advance, children in rural and low-income areas have access to more and more information and resources. This, in theory, would cause the education gap between children who grow up in low income areas and children who grow up in high income areas to shrink, but research shows that the gap in performance between high-income and low-income students is as big as ever. A study done by Mikhail Zinshteyn of The Atlantic found that when American households are organized into four income groups, 24-year-olds from the top two groups accounted for 77 percent of the bachelors degrees awarded in 2016. This means that a vast majority of bachelors degrees across the country are still going to students who grew up in high income areas. This report looks just at students in Georgia who applied to the Georgia Institute of Technology to see how economic factors affect acceptance to this particular institute.
Georgia Tech is a state school, so a certain percentage of students accepted must be from Georgia. The overall acceptance rate from 2018 was 23% with the high being in-state at 35% and the low being international students at 10%. Only the data from students in Georgia was looked at. Admissions data came from the Georgia Tech Office of Institutional Research and Planning, which provided all the admission data for every relevant high school (10>= students enrolled at GT) in GA. Median household income data for each relevant zip code was gathered from Zip Atlas and the US Department of Agriculture Economic Research. In the analysis, four different simple linear regressions were run with ZIP Code income as the explanatory variable and different admissions factors as the response variables to test for a significant relationship. In particular, the admissions factors that were looked at were:
* Average ACT score
* Number of students who applied to Georgia Tech
* Number of students who were accepted into Georgia Tech
* Average year one GPA at Georgia Tech

A regression and scatterplot were created for each pair of variables. General findings show that there is a positive correlation between higher zip incomes and more people getting accepted into tech. A possible reason for this is that higher income areas have access to better resources to prepare them for college such as: SAT/ACT prep courses, better education systems, academic counselors, and a plethora of AP courses. Lower income areas may not have access to these resources. This is supported by the positive correlation between ACT scores and Zip Income. Although it appears tech accepts an increasing number of applicants from higher income areas compared to lower income areas, the average year one GPA at tech versus Zip Income shows that students from all income levels are equally prepared for the rigors of Georgia Tech. .

Business Problem

Does a higher household income indicate a higher likelihood of acceptance to the Georgia Institute of Technology? The commonly known factors that make up a college applicant are ACT, High School GPA, number of AP courses, etc. As it becomes more and more difficult to get into Georgia Tech, we want to analyze if there are any non obvious factors giving applicants and advantage over others.

Data Summary

The following is a summary of the data that the group used for this project and how the final data frame was created.

First, we used the Internet to download a .csv file containing different bits of information about all of the public schools in the state of Georgia. We found this .csv file on the Georgia Department of Educations website. This file contains the schools full name, system name, school address, school city, school zip, and more. For most schools, system name was the same as county. We used this to get an initial dataset with location data on all the high schools in the state of Georgia.

allGASchools <- read_csv("ga_public_school_contact_list.csv",col_types = cols()) %>%
  filter(FAC_SCHTYPE == "H")%>%
  select(SYSTEM_NAME, SCHOOL_NAME, COUNTY, SCHOOL_ADDRESS, SCHOOL_CITY, SCHOOL_ZIP)
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.4.4
allGASchools[433,3]="Gwinnett County"

Next, we downloaded a .csv file containing income data for all of the counties in Georgia. This .csv was issued by the United States Department of Agriculture. We then used a merged by county to combine the Georgia high schools dataframe with the income data frame. Some of the data fields didnt align exactly so we had to manually input some data. For example, we had to paste Fulton County in the county field for all schools that were in the Atlanta Public Schools school system. (Most schools system name was the same as county name. Atlanta Public Schools is one of the exceptions.)

IncomeTable <- read_csv("IncomeData.csv",col_types = cols()) %>%
  filter(State == "GA") %>%
  select(State, Area_name, Median_Household_Income_2016) 

IncomeTable[[2]] <- sub(", GA", "", IncomeTable[[2]])

names(IncomeTable)[2] <- paste("COUNTY")



IncomeSchoolsTable <- merge(allGASchools, IncomeTable, by="COUNTY", all.x = TRUE)

IncomeSchoolsTable[88, 3]="Alan C Pope High School"
IncomeSchoolsTable[129, 3]="Arabia Mountain High School"
IncomeSchoolsTable[460, 1] = "Gwinnett County"
IncomeSchoolsTable[84, 3] = "Carlton J Kell High School"

The next step was to manually create a .csv file containing all of the admissions information for Georgia Tech. The admissions data is provided by the Georgia Tech Office of Institutional Research and Planning. This data is from all Georgia high schools with 10 or more students enrolled from 2012-2016.

We merged the acceptance dataframe with the dataframe created in the step above. The result is a dataframe that contains all of the schools that has 10 or more students enrolled at Georgia Tech and the income data for the school.

AcceptanceTable <- read_csv("AcceptanceData.csv",col_types = cols())

FinalTable <- mutate(FinalTable, Acceptance_rate = Accepted/Applied)

Data Summary Part 2

We realized that using county income for our project was a little too broad. We needed data that was more narrow and representative of the high schools we were interested in. So, we decided to gather data for zip code median household income. We gathered data from zipatlas.com using the html_nodes data scraping technique learned in class.

Description and Interpretation of Results

In this analysis, 4 different simple linear regressions were run with Zip Income (the median income in a zipcode) as the explanatory variable and different admissions factors as the response variables. In particular, the admissions factors that were looked at were: average ACT score, number of students who applied to Georgia Tech, number of students who were accepted into Georgia Tech, and average year one GPA at Georgia Tech. In an initial attempt to run the regression with just Zip Income, some problems arose because there was a very small amount of variation in the response variables, but a very large amount of variation in the Zip Income explanatory variable. To alleviate this a log transformation of Zip Income was used to account for the variation. The result was a more accurate linear regression.
We ran a regression and created a scatterplot for each pair of variables. General findings show that there is a positive correlation between median household zip code income and number accepted into Georgia Tech. One major reason for this is that higher income areas have access to better resources to prepare them for college such as: SAT/ACT prep courses, better education systems, academic counselors, and a plethora of Advanced Placement courses. Lower income areas may not have access to comparable resources. This is supported by the positive correlation between ACT scores and Zip Income. Although it appears Tech accepts an increasing number of applicants from higher income areas compared to lower income areas, the average year one GPA at Tech versus Zip Income regression and scatterplot show that students from higher income levels have slightly higher year one GPAs, but all admitted Tech students perform pretty comparably despite income levels.

Business Implications

The findings of the research project have many important implications for businesses and Georgia Tech, particularly for admissions decisions. The following is a discussion of some of the implications that our results have for businesses.

One of the major reasons that Georgia Tech might be admitting more prospective students from higher income areas is because family income not only has a huge correlation with the chance that a kid gets into college, but of that persons likelihood of actually graduating (Sherman 2015). Georgia Tech doesnt want to admit students who they believe might not graduate because it affects the graduation rates from the Institute and portrays the Institute in a negative light.

In a study conducted by Forbes, data scientists looked at Bachelors Degree attainment rates by age 24 for dependent family members who entered college. The study found that if your family is from the top quartile of income and you get accepted to college, you have a 99% chance to finish at least a bachelors (Sherman 2015). Perhaps Georgia Tech is accepting more students from high income areas because they know these students are much more likeley to graduate. Or perhaps Georgia Tech is accepting the best applicants who seem to be likeley graduates and it just so happens that they are from high income areas.

Our results also indicate that students applying to Georgia Tech from schools in higher income areas will have a slightly higher year one GPA. Students with higher GPAs are usually more likely to receive better/higher paying job offers upon graduation, and so Georgia Tech might admit these students with the prospect of receiving more future alumni donations from them. Again, Georgia Tech might be accepting more applicants from higher income areas; or the applicants they believe to be succesful at Georgia Tech are coincidentally from higher income areas.

Students from lower income families/zip codes might also require larger amounts of financial aid. Georgia Techs 2016 endowment was $1.844B, so while this seems like a lot of money (which it is), Georgia Tech is still on a budget and cannot grant financial aid to every single student. If a student is seeking financial aid and not extremely competitive, the Institute might not accept that student because they want to reserve their financial aid for more competitive applicants.

Lower income high schools dont have the resources to compete with higher income schools. When an applicant applies to Georgia Tech, the applicants high school also submits a high school profile to the Institute. This school profile includes but is not limited to information such as college admissions rates, advanced placement classes offered by the school, share of students who qualify for free and reduced-price lunches, demographics, etc. Lower income schools simply dont have the resources to provide more than the bare minimum information, whereas higher income schools have access to much more detailed and accurate school profiles. In fact, admissions officers were 26% more likeley to recommend low-income students when provided detailed information about them and their high schools (Berman 2017). Georgia Tech is accepting the most qualified applicants; however, these applicants might appear to be more qualified based off the amount of resources/income that their respective high schools have. Higher income schools also offer more extensive college counseling, application essay practice, SAT/ACT prep courses, etc.

Lastly, our results state that students from higher income areas will have higher ACT scores. This is likeley a result of two major factors. First, standardized testing prep courses and tutors are very expensive. Instructor led courses can cost up to $1,000 while private tutors demand the high price of up to $195 per session. Higher income applicants can afford these steep prices while lower income applicants might not. Many private schools as well as high income/resource public schools offer students an SAT/ACT prep course that students can take for a semester in order to prepare for their standardized tests. Again, high income schools have the resources to offer these courses while low income schools do not.
